nglish and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Aevery</i>, a Norman form of   Alfred  . Among the 17th-century Puritan settlers in New England, there was some confusion with   Averill  . Compare   Averett  .","Altered form of French Canadian <b>Hévey</b> (see   Hevey  ). Compare   Avey   3.","History: Christopher Avery emigrated from England to Salem, MA, in or before 1630. — William Avery (alias Averill) was one of the Puritan settlers who emigrated from England to Ipswich, MA, in or <i>c.</i> 1637. — Some of the American bearers of the surname <i>Avery</i> are descendants of Nicolas Hévé/Devé from France, who was in QC by 1672 (see   Hevey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Avara","meanings":["Altered form of English   Avery  . See also   Avera  .","Italian (Sicily): from the feminine form of <b>Avaro</b>, a nickname from <i>avaro</i> ‘avaricious, mean, miserly’. This surname is very rare in Italy."]},{"name":"Averill","meanings":["English:","apparently from the name of the month (April), Middle English <i>averil</i>, Old French <i>avrill</i>, Latin <i>aprīlis</i>, perhaps with reference to freshness of temperament, or youth, or possibly to the changeable weather of the month.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Haverhill in Suffolk, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>. The placename derives from either Old English <i>hæfera</i> ‘oats’ or <i>hæfer</i> ‘he-goat’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Avera","meanings":["Altered form of English   Avery  .","History: Richard Avery, from Fillongley, Warwickshire, is recorded in Surry, VA, in 1672. The surname was changed to <i>Avera</i> in the following generation and later also to <i>Avara</i>. A Jacob Avera is recorded in Johnson County, NC in 1764."]},{"name":"Avary","meanings":["English: variant of   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Every","meanings":["English (southwestern): variant of   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Alfred","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Arianne, Armand, Camille, Germine, Jacques, Jean-Claude, Magalie, Marcel, Michel, Patrice.","English, French, German, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and African (mainly Tanzania): from the Middle English personal name <i>Alfred</i>, <i>Elfred</i>, Old English <i>Ælfrǣd</i> ‘elf counsel’. This owed its popularity as a personal name in England to the fame of the West Saxon king Alfred the Great (849–899), who defeated the Danes, keeping them out of Wessex, and whose court was a great center of learning and culture."]},{"name":"Hevey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Nicolle.","French Canadian (<b>Hévey</b>): altered form of French <b>Hévé</b>, itself a variant or an altered form of <b>Devé</b>, an unflattering nickname from <i>desvé</i> ‘mad, insane’. The surname <i>Devé</i> originates from Normandy. Compare   Avery   2 and   Avey   3.","Irish (Meath): variant of   Heaphy  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Avery was born about 1510, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1510–":"umbes 1510–Surnud","1530–1626":"1530–1626","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","about 1510":"umbes 1510","1626":"1626","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1510–":"noin 1510–Kuollut","1530–1626":"1530–1626","1510–Male":"1510–Kuollut","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","about 1510":"noin 1510","1626":"1626","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1510–":"environ 1510–Décédé","1530–1626":"1530–1626","1510–Male":"1510–Décédé","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","about 1510":"environ 1510","1626":"1626","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"John Avery est né environ 1510, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1510–":"um 1510–V